Jai Singh, Jaipur and The Jantar Mantar

Timeline of Events

1688

Jai Singh is born to Maharaja Bishan Singh of the Kuchwaha dynasty of the Rajput clan in Amber in Rajasthan.

1700

Jai Singh ascends the throne in Amber at the age of 12

1707

Emperor Aurangzeb dies. Emperor Bahadur Shah Zafar I ascends the throne in Delhi. Jai Singhâ€™s kingdom is annexed and Amber is granted to Jai Singhâ€™s younger brother, Bijay Singh.

1710

Jai Singh is back in favour with Emperor Bahadur Shah Zafar I

1719

Emperor Muhammad Shah II ascends the throne in Delhi. Jai Singh is appointed as Governor of Malwa

1720

Formal coronation of Emperor Muhammad Shah in Delhi when Jai Singh meets him and discusses the observatory.

1721-24

Jai Singh constructs an observatory in Delhi (another Jantar Mantar).

1724

Construction of the Jaipur Jantar Mantar commences

1723-30

Jai Singh constructs observatories in Mathura, Ujjain and Benares

1727

Jaipur replaces Amber as the capital city

1725â€“28

Jai Singh conducts scientific missions to Europe and publishes his own astronomical tables, the Zij-i-Muhammad Shahi, named after Mughal ruler Muhammad Shah II. This series of three books replaced the previously used al-Tusiâ€™s Zij-i-Ilahi and Ulugh Begâ€™s Zij-i-Gurgani.

1732

The second edition of Zij-i-Muhammad Shahi is published.
The construction of the royal palace is completed.

1734

The Jaipur Jantar Mantar is completed.

1743

Jai Singh II dies.

The Story of
Jantar Mantar

The Jantar Mantar has a compelling presence in Jaipur. Its history feels palpable to those who explore its well-organized instruments. Every stone, every instrument has a story to tell and at every turn, there is something to transport you back in time.
